\section{Introduction}

This document is intended to help describe how to undertake analyses introduced as examples in the Second Edition of the \emph{Statistical Sleuth} (2002) by Fred Ramsey and Dan Schafer.
More information about the book can be found at \url{http://www.proaxis.com/~panorama/home.htm}.

This work leverages initiatives undertaken by Project MOSAIC (\url{http://www.mosaic-web.org}), an NSF-funded project to improve the teaching of statistics, calculus, science and computing in the undergraduate curriculum. In particular, we utilize the 
\pkg{mosaic} package, which was written to simplify the use of R for introductory statistics courses. To use a package within R, it must be installed (one time), and loaded (each session). The package can be installed using the following command:
<<install_mosaic,eval=FALSE>>=
install.packages('mosaic')               # note the quotation marks
@
Once this is installed, it can be loaded by running the command:
<<load_mosaic,eval=FALSE>>=
require(mosaic)
@
This
needs to be done once per session.

We also set some options to improve legibility of graphs and output.
<<eval=TRUE>>=
trellis.par.set(theme=col.mosaic())  # get a better color scheme for lattice
options(digits=3)
@

The goal of this document is to demonstate how to calculate the quantities described in Chapter 9: Multiple Regression using RStudio.

\section{Effects of light on meadowfoam flowering}
Do different amounts of light affect the growth of meadowfoam (a small plant used to create seed oil)?  This is the question addressed in case study 9.1.1 in the \emph{Sleuth}.  

\subsection{Data coding, summary statistics and graphical display} 
<<>>=
light = read.csv("http://www.math.smith.edu/~nhorton/sleuth/case0901.csv")
@

<<>>=
# create a better named variable for day24
light$day24 = relevel(as.factor(ifelse(light$TIME==1, "late", "early")), ref="late")
@

Display 9.2 (page 237)
<<>>=
summary(light)
favstats(FLOWERS ~ INTENS | day24, data=light)
@

The following displays the scatterplot of the average number of flowers per
plant versus the applied light intensity for each of the 12 experimental units. (Display 9.3 page 238 of \emph{Sleuth})

<<>>=
xyplot(FLOWERS ~ INTENS, groups=day24, type=c("p", "r", "smooth"), data=light, 
       auto.key=TRUE, xlab="light intensity (mu mol/m^2/sec)", ylab="average number of flowers")
@


\subsection{Multiple linear regression model}

We then can fit a multiple linear regression model that specifies parallel regression lines for the mea  number of flowers as a function of light intensity as interpreted on page 237.
<<>>=
lm1 = lm(FLOWERS ~ INTENS + day24, data=light)
summary(lm1)
confint(lm1, level=.95) # 95% confidence intervals  
@

We can also fit a mulitple linear regression with an ineraction between light intensity and timing of its initiation as shown in Display 9.14 (page 256) and interpreted on page 237.
<<>>=
lm2 = lm(FLOWERS ~ INTENS * day24, data=light)
summary(lm2)
@

\section{Why do some mammals have large brains?}
What characteristics predict large brains in elephants?   This is the question addressed in case study 9.1.2 in the \emph{Sleuth}.  

\subsection{Data coding and summary statistics}

<<>>=
mammals = read.csv("http://www.math.smith.edu/~nhorton/sleuth/case0902.csv")
mammals$logbrain = log(mammals$BRAIN); mammals$logbody = log(mammals$BODY)
mammals$loggest = log(mammals$GESTATION); mammals$loglitter = log(mammals$LITTER)
@

<<>>=
summary(mammals)
@

\subsection{Graphical presentation}

The following displays a simple (unadorned) pairs plot (akin to Display 9.10 on page 252).

<<>>=
pairs(mammals[c("BRAIN", "BODY", "GESTATION", "LITTER")])
@

We can make it fancier if we like.
<<>>=
  panel.hist = function(x, ...)
  {
    usr = par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
    par(usr = c(usr[1:2], 0, 1.5) )
    h = hist(x, plot=FALSE)
    breaks = h$breaks; nB = length(breaks)
    y = h$counts; y = y/max(y)
    rect(breaks[-nB], 0, breaks[-1], y, col="cyan", ...)
  }

panel.lm = function(x, y, col=par("col"), bg=NA, 
                    pch=par("pch"), cex=1, col.lm="red", ...) 
{
  points(x, y, pch=pch, col=col, bg=bg, cex=cex)
  ok = is.finite(x) & is.finite(y)
  if (any(ok)) 
    abline(lm(y[ok] ~ x[ok]))
}
@

Below displays a fancier pairs plot.

<<>>=
  pairs(~ BRAIN + BODY + GESTATION + LITTER, 
        lower.panel=panel.smooth, diag.panel=panel.hist, 
        upper.panel=panel.lm, data=mammals)
@


Here is a fancier pairs plot using the log-transformed variables (akin to Display 9.11 on page 253).

<<>>=
  pairs(~ logbrain + logbody + loggest + loglitter, 
              lower.panel=panel.smooth, diag.panel=panel.hist, 
              upper.panel=panel.lm, data=mammals)
@


The following displays a jittered scatterplot of log brain weight as a function of log litter size (akin to Display 9.12 on page 254).

<<>>=
  xyplot(logbrain ~ jitter(loglitter), data=mammals)
@


Below displays a jittered scatterplot using the original data on a log-transformed axis (akin to Display 9.12 on page 254).

<<>>=
  xyplot(BRAIN ~ jitter(LITTER), scales=list(y=list(log=TRUE),
                                             x=list(log=TRUE)), data=mammals)
@


The following displays a jittered scatterplot using the original data stratified by body weight on a log-transformed axis (akin to Display 9.13 on page 255).

